name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hodgson","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hog, prudent, and sun, son, meaning a prudent son"],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Hodgson Lausoun was born about 1370, in Durham, England. He had at least 1 son with Ann Bainbridge. He died about 1440, in Romaldkirk, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 72."},"et":{"about 1370–about 1440":"umbes 1370–umbes 1440","1370–1440":"1370–1440","1400–1441":"1400–1441","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1400":"1400","1441":"1441","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","about 1440":"umbes 1440","1370":"1370","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Andrew Hubbard, Durham, England":"Durham, England","Romaldkirk, Yorkshire, England":"Romaldkirk, North Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1370–about 1440":"noin 1370–noin 1440","1370–1440":"1370–1440","1400–1441":"1400–1441","about 1370":"noin 1370","1400":"1400","1441":"1441","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","about 1440":"noin 1440","1370":"1370","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire,